We are nurturing orgs across North America dedicated to building direct democracy and balance with non-human nature from the ground up. We are building the new world now, neighborhood by neighborhood, city by city. Starting with our labor, the land beneath our feet, and technology.
Building a new world in the shell of the old one as it collapses around you is a daunting task. Where to begin?
These are our guiding principles as a network. This is what we stand on. What binds us. developed on centuries of history, experience, and research. Please Read them carefully.
Symbiosis is a decentralized network with core members active all across the continent, and with a wide range of focuses. Poke your head in and See where discussions are here.
Want to see what’s already going on around you and how you can get involved? Tap in here.
There are a million and one pieces that go into world-building. To explore “nuts and bolts,” or ideas for the task, check out the educational resources below.
It’s not too late to do things differently. Let’s work together to live as if we are already free.
If you’re looking to explore or even begin building with those in the Symbiosis network, this is the best place to start.

So you want to quit your job, get together with cool people, and figure out how to actually live under comfortable conditions without having to worry about food, housing, or internet connection 😤… You want to go and build cooperative and communal communities without bosses and landlords, but in a way that affords you space and privacy (i.e., a way that isn’t on some weird cult shit 😵‍💫…

Under our current conditions, the struggle for democratic control can begin in two general areas:
So, if looking to start “getting free” from the here and the now, here are some ideas on how to begin, starting from where you are:

Together, we can create institutions of real democracy and human connection out of the places we live and work. Through organizing participatory institutions at the grassroots, we can meet our immediate human needs and form a new basis of power, organizing society in parallel against capitalism and the state.
This framework—of building popular power outside the governing institutions of our present system, to challenge and displace those institutions through truly democratic ones of our own—is called “dual power.”
This dual power strategy can help sustain our communities under capitalism, channel our collective action to fight back more effectively, and eventually supplant the institutions of capitalism to become the governing structures of a liberated society.

As the branches of the tree grow outwards, its roots dig deeper.
Our organizations have come together because we recognize that the changes required to secure our future are more than what each of us can do at the local level. We need to escalate our strategy towards a strong network, or confederation.
By organizing locally, we are pushed to embrace experimentation, but the lessons of experimentation should circulate between us so that we can dedicate our energies to pushing ahead into new territories of radical possibility. The future of our movement will depend on the rapid cultivation of radical democracy in all sorts of communities across the continent.
For this, we need the visibility of a common platform, with the capacity to support people through developing their own initiatives or connect them to those that already exist.
Ruling-class power is organized globally, and if democracy is to win, we must be organized at that scale as well.
Our full launch statement is available here:
Curious why this is our approach?

In your current workplaces and or buildings controlled by the ruling-class overlords.

Members of the Symbiosis network move within both of these two general “struggle” areas, and many within the network would probably argue that struggle for democratic control in both of these areas is ultimately necessary, but since most of the movements that inspire our Member and Partner orgs are grounded in struggle area #2 (outside, and on the fringes), this is where we will begin our introductory guide…

See who around you is interested in doing the same thing. This could mean starting discussions around systems change with people at your job, in your family, or in your immediate neighborhood (putting the feelers out there); or it could be searching through [insert Dual Power Map or future directory for Dual Power App] to see who around you is already building in this kind of way on some level, and tapping in to build trust, learn, and/or support.

Assuming there is nothing going on around you already (this is going to be the case 99% of the time for the foreseeable future), and assuming you are able to find a considerable amount of people who are interested in living without bosses or landlords (for more on how to find, galvanize, and inspire people to start building dual power, see our guide *here* and consider joining the Symbiosis Discord space while we support development of the Dual Power App), choose one area most immediate and important to the group as it relates to both your needs and the needs of your surrounding community (food, housing, mutual aid, etc.), and begin research on how to develop cooperative institutions and social practices that can address these things during any time you have off of the clock. Just some of the main ones many within Symbiosis are working around are:
  • Mutual Aid Networks
  • Community Land Trusts (CLTs)
  • Worker Self-Directed Enterprises (WSDEs)
  • Worker Cooperatives (Co-ops)
  • Cooperative Banking (Credit Unions)
  • People’s Assemblies

After beginning to make headway on an “anchor” institution that makes sense for the size and focus of your group, consider discussing means of further outreach to gather more members, and begin researching other institutions that can reinforce and support operations, as well as those most invested in the work. The ultimate goal is to develop a grassroots, self-reinforcing, self-sustaining ecosystem of cooperative institutions that are inviting to much larger amounts of people over time, and help more people within the community meet needs and live comfortably without subjecting themselves to wage slavery. We would call these grassroots ecosystems “eco-communities” (or “dual power projects”).

Along with those you’ve connected with in your neighborhood, county, and/or state, tap into the Symbiosis network via Discord [and the Dual Power App], and begin to connect with other Dual Power Projects throughout the country to see what their community needs are, and how you can begin to support each other’s efforts in expanding.
These are our guiding principles as a network. This is what we stand on. What binds us. Developed on centuries of history, experience, and research. Please read them carefully.

We believe that all people should have an equal voice in determining our common future. We organize for self-determination by having decision-making power come from the bottom up. All power to the people.

We oppose all systems of domination. We fight against capitalism, patriarchy, imperialism, white supremacy, and all other forms of oppression, and lift up the voices of the most marginalized. We embrace Martin Luther King's call for a radical revolution of values, and uphold feminist, egalitarian, and indigenous values against colonial, capitalist, and hierarchical values.

The fate of humanity is intertwined with all other life on Earth. We embrace the holistic and reconstructive dimensions of indigenous knowledge and ecological science. Capitalism is killing life on our planet, and we are fighting to sustain life by re-harmonizing human societies with the rest of the natural world.

Economic democracy is essential for the preservation of our ecosystems and the self-determination of our communities. We seek to abolish the profit system and place economic decision-making in the hands of communities and workers through communal, cooperative economics and an ethic of mutual aid.

Our movement seeks to transform our oppressive society through collective resistance to the destructive capitalist system, together with the creation of living alternatives. We organize for dual power in our communities by building democracy and mutual aid outside the state, to confront the present system while creating the future that will replace it. We are building the new world in the shell of the old.

We celebrate the fullest range of human identities and experiences in our movement. Our diversity and our relationships with one another are our greatest strengths. We believe that this whole is greater than the sum of its parts, and that our interdependence and common humanity unite us. The road is long, and we must walk it together.
It’s not too late to do things differently. Let’s work together to live as if we are already free.
